**Project: Self-hosted LLM inference on Clore.AI GPU marketplace**

## Platform: Clore.AI

Clore.AI is a P2P GPU rental marketplace. You rent Docker containers on other people's GPUs. You don't control the host OS — only what runs inside the container.

**How Clore's boot process works:**
- You specify a Docker image and a "startup script" when creating an order
- Clore's SSH Autoinstall replaces the container entrypoint with S6 overlay (a process supervisor) that runs SSH + `/root/onstart.sh`
- **Startup script** = runs ONCE on first container creation. Used for installing software and downloading models
- **`/root/onstart.sh`** = runs EVERY time the container starts/restarts. This is where the llama-server command lives
- After writing onstart.sh, call `s6-svc -r /var/run/s6/services/onstart` to trigger it. If S6 is ready it runs immediately; if not, S6 runs it when it finishes deploying

**Clore gotchas we discovered the hard way:**
- The startup script runs in a minimal shell with a stripped PATH. Tools installed via `apt install` during the script often can't be found by name immediately — the shell doesn't see them. This is why we moved to building a custom Docker image with tools pre-baked
- `huggingface-cli` is deprecated; the new command is `hf`
- `hf download --local-dir` doesn't reliably place files where expected on these containers
- Model downloads can produce 0-byte files silently — always verify filesize before proceeding
- SSH can take several minutes to become available even after Clore says "deployed"
- Images that force a non-root default user don't work with SSH Autoinstall

