## Model: Qwen3.6-35B-A3B

Mixture-of-Experts. 35B total parameters, only 3B active per token (256 experts, 8 activated + 1 shared). Practically this means:
- VRAM: needs space for all 35B params (like any 35B model)
- Compute per token: like a 3B model, so very fast (~100-135 tok/s on single 3090)
- Using Unsloth `UD-Q4_K_XL` GGUF quantization — 22.1GB on disk

## Docker image

Base image: `ghcr.io/ggml-org/llama.cpp:server-cuda`

Custom Dockerfile to pre-bake dependencies (avoids PATH issues in startup script):

```dockerfile
FROM ghcr.io/ggml-org/llama.cpp:server-cuda
RUN apt update -y && DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive apt install -y wget curl aria2 python3 python3-pip && pip install huggingface_hub[hf_transfer] --break-system-packages && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
ENV HF_HUB_ENABLE_HF_TRANSFER=1
RUN mkdir -p /models
```

Push to Docker Hub, use as the Clore container image.

## Working startup script (final version)

```bash
#!/bin/sh
mkdir -p /models
MODEL="/models/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf"
URL="https://huggingface.co/unsloth/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-GGUF/resolve/main/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf"
export HF_TOKEN="hf_your_token_here"

if [ ! -f "$MODEL" ]; then
    echo "[$(date)] Starting model download..." >> /var/log/startup.log

    echo "[$(date)] Trying aria2c..." >> /var/log/startup.log
    aria2c -x 16 -s 16 -k 1M -d /models -o Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf \
        --header="Authorization: Bearer $HF_TOKEN" \
        "$URL" >> /var/log/startup.log 2>&1

    if [ ! -f "$MODEL" ]; then
        echo "[$(date)] aria2c failed, trying wget..." >> /var/log/startup.log
        wget --header="Authorization: Bearer $HF_TOKEN" \
            -O "$MODEL" "$URL" >> /var/log/startup.log 2>&1
    fi

    if [ ! -f "$MODEL" ]; then
        echo "[$(date)] wget failed, trying curl..." >> /var/log/startup.log
        curl -L -H "Authorization: Bearer $HF_TOKEN" \
            -o "$MODEL" "$URL" >> /var/log/startup.log 2>&1
    fi
fi

FILESIZE=$(stat -c%s "$MODEL" 2>/dev/null || echo 0)
if [ "$FILESIZE" -lt 1000000000 ]; then
    echo "[$(date)] ERROR: All download methods failed ($FILESIZE bytes)" >> /var/log/startup.log
    rm -f "$MODEL"
    exit 1
fi

echo "[$(date)] Download complete ($FILESIZE bytes)" >> /var/log/startup.log

cat > /root/onstart.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/sh
export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/app:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH
/app/llama-server \
  -m /models/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf \
  --host 0.0.0.0 \
  --port 8080 \
  -ngl 999 \
  -fa on \
  -c 98304 \
  --cache-type-k q8_0 \
  --cache-type-v q8_0 \
  --no-mmap \
  --jinja >> /var/log/llama-server.log 2>&1
EOF

chmod +x /root/onstart.sh
s6-svc -r /var/run/s6/services/onstart
```

## llama-server flags and why each matters

- **`-ngl 999`** — offload all layers to GPU
- **`-fa on`** — flash attention. Must be `-fa on` not just `-fa` on newer llama.cpp builds (we hit this error)
- **`-c 98304`** — 96K context. Proven working on single 3090 with Q4_K_XL + q8_0 KV cache. Uses 23.1GB of 24.5GB VRAM with 1.4GB headroom
- **`--cache-type-k q8_0 --cache-type-v q8_0`** — the key optimization. Halves KV cache VRAM with no measurable quality loss on Qwen3.6. This is how we went from 8K to 98K context on the same GPU
- **`--no-mmap`** — loads weights fully into VRAM instead of memory-mapping from disk. Better for GPU-only inference
- **`--jinja`** — enables Jinja chat templates, required for Qwen3.6's chat format

## What we confirmed works

- Q4_K_XL at 98K context on single 3090: stable, 1.4GB headroom, server reports healthy
- q8_0 KV cache quantization: no quality loss, halves KV cache footprint
- aria2c with 16 parallel connections: ~52 MB/s download speed on Clore nodes
- Three-tier download fallback (aria2c → wget → curl): handles whatever tools are available
- HuggingFace token passed via Authorization header to all download methods

## What we confirmed does NOT work or help

- **Speculative decoding on this model:** extensively benchmarked, every configuration (ngram-cache, ngram-mod, classic draft with Qwen3.5-0.8B) is 3-12% slower on 3090. The MoE architecture causes expert thrashing during draft verification
- **Ollama:** wraps llama.cpp but hides KV cache quantization, flash attention, and batch size controls. llama-server directly gives ~1.4x speed and 2x context
- **`hf download`/`huggingface-cli`:** unreliable on Clore containers. Downloads to cache instead of target dir, or doesn't find the binary
- **`-fa` without `on`:** newer llama.cpp builds require `-fa on`, bare `-fa` throws an error
- **Tensor split mode (`-sm tensor`) for multi-GPU:** not implemented for MoE architectures including Qwen3.6

## Next step: 262K context on 2x RTX 3090

The plan is to rent a 2x RTX 3090 server on Clore (roughly $0.40/hr on-demand, much less on spot). 48GB total VRAM fits Q4_K_XL (22.1GB) with ~26GB for KV cache, enough for full 262K context.

llama.cpp auto-detects both GPUs and splits layers across them using pipeline parallelism (layer split). No extra flags needed — same startup script but with `-c 262144` instead of `-c 98304`.

Speed won't double with two GPUs because pipeline parallelism is sequential (tokens pass GPU0 → GPU1). Expect ~80-100 tok/s. The second GPU is purely for VRAM capacity, not speed.

Alternative: could run Q8 quantization (38.5GB) across 2x 3090 for better quality at 262K context.

